{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_greenville_ver01/data/sn95047212/00529042334/1958031301/0054.xml":{"full_text":"Page 2\nlabor (Citizen\nA GENERAL NEWSPAPER\nDEVOTED TO THE BEST INTERESTS OF ORGANIZED LABOR\nPublished Every Thursday by\nThe LABOR PRESS, Inc Charles F. Towle, President\nP. 0. Box 828 Phone PL 7-5031\nAdvertising Rates on Request\nSubscription Rate 12.00 Per Year\nEntered as second-class postal matter October 1, 1920, at the\nPost Office at Miami, Fla., under Act of Congress of March 3, 1879\nCHAS. F. TOWLE Editor\nJ. ED ISOM 1 Advertising Director\nOfficial Organ of DADE COUNTY FEDERATION OF LABOR, MIAMI BUILD-\nING TRADES COUNCIL, FLORIDA FEDERATION OF LABOR\nCITIZEN ADVISORY COMMITTEE\nEducational Committee of the Dade County Federation of Labor\n\"IFere it not for the labor press, the labor movement would not be what it is\ntoday, and any man who tries to injure a labor paper is a traitor to the cause.\u201d\n\u2014SAMUEL GOMPERS.\nThe Jobless Can't Wait\nFor well over a decade organized labor has fought to\nmodernize and update the unemployment compensation\nsystem, warning that it was being distorted and weakened\nto the point that it could not cope with a serious recession.\nThe recession has hit and the glaring inadequacies\nof jobless benefits, their duration and the various quali\nfication procedures have been more clearly defined than\never before.\nThe 20-year rivalry between states to attract new in\ndustry, using the unemployment compensation system as a\npawn, has resulted in jobless workers drawing only one\nthird of their normal wages in benefits, a far cry from the\noriginal goal of providing a worker thrown out of work\nwith at least one-half of his normal wages.\nWith workers rapidly using up their jobless insurance\nbenefits and with unemployment increasing, the need for\nimmediate action by Congress to set new federal minimum\nstandards is acute. The bills introduced by Sen. John F.\nKennedy (D-Mass.) and Rep. Eugene McCarthy (D-Minn.)\nmeet this need and should get top priority as a key weapon\nin battling recession.\nFive years ago the Eisenhower Administration called\non the states to enact minimum standards as a defense\nagainst economic recession. It has repeated this call every\nyear since but not one state has met the standards the Presi\ndent has requested.\nThe time is long past for action to set up federal\nminimum standards, long past for the Administration to\nadmit that its appeal for state action has collapsed and\nto swing its support behind the Kennedy-McCarthy bill.\nEvery moment of delay visits new hardships on the\ngrowing number of unemployed seeking to keep their\nheads afloat.\nI- Compliments of 4\nREDLAND TAVERN j\nThe Right Place to Meet Your Friends 4\n4\nRESTAURANT-BAR PACKAGE STORE\n-t\n\nAvocado Dr. and Federal Hwy. 1 4\n2 Miles North of Homestead, Fla. Ph. CI 7-9972 4\nt...\nZ 9\nI uz\nI /Durome\u2019s I\nI I\nSUNSHINE FASHIONS* I\n*r\u00a9g. U. S. pat. off.\nv Miami Miami Beach Ft. I.auderdale West Palm Beach C\nSTUART\nAUTO SEAT COVERS COMPLETE INTERIORS\nI\u2605\u2605\nCI'STOM COVERS AND CONVERTIBLE TOPS\n1116 N. Federal Hwy., Homestead, Fla. Vs\nV Phone Circle 7-7438 y\nLABOR CITIZEN\n\u20227\nMarch 13, 1958\nTowle Talks:\n(Continued from Page 1)\nwould have you think they can go\nit alone.\nMake no mistake. The United\nFund does not tell you who you\nshould give to or who not to give\nto. The whole purpose of the UF\nis to eliminate so many expensive\ndrives and thereby reduce the cost\nof fund-raising to the point where\na larger percentage of your dollar\ngoes to your favored agency.\nCSA Offers\n(Continued from page 1)\nmic level;\u201d and the use of payroll\ndeduction plans, wherever possible\nand feasible, to enable contribu\ntors to spread their gift over a lon\nger period of time.\nThe pamphlet states that con\ntributions should be truly volun\ntary, adding \u201cthere is no room for\npressure or coercion at any time.\u201d\nThe CSA publication points out\nthat \u201cthe best way to build popular\nsupport for voluntary social agen\ncies is through year-round pro\ngrams of education and service.\u201d\nCopies of \u201cGuidelines to Giving\u201d\ncan be obtained for 1c each by\nwriting to: AFL-CIO Community\nService Activities, 9 East 40th\nStreet, New York 16, N. Y.\nDEFINITION\nEisenhower Cocktail: Business on\nthe Rocks.\nC. J. HOKE\nIncome Tax Specialist\nSpecial Consideration\nGiven To Members of\nOrganized Labor\n1653 S. W. 13th Street\nPhone FR 4-6730\nAlo\nyiyjil*y> F: \u201dx\nw O 5 m\nO O\n\u25a0I aiMii W W W;\nMR WM 4\nWB wwl s\nw\n.*^B\u00ae ''/j/CSS* rlffb'\nIt\nMm? UmK Jabs\nHP\ntgood reasons\nto buy\nFlorida-made\nproducts\nSome 7,500 different products ore Hado, frown, or processed boro in Florida.\nGifts and novelties top sporting equipment foods sportswear\nfurniture jewelry we can\u2019t list them all but we can assure you that you\nalways buy right when you buy products with the made-in-Flonda label.\nShare Florida's sunshine with the folks back home get in the swim, yourself... buy\nand give Honda-made products!\nHORID POWER LIGHT COMPANY\nAnnual Election For\nElection of Robert J. Fitzgerald\nas corporation treasurer of the\nBishopric-Green-Fielden advertis\ning agency, and Mrs. Natalie\nGuerra as secretary, has been an\nnounced by Karl Bishopric, agency\npresident.\nFitzgerald, who joined the or\nganization a year ago, holds the\nposition of controller for the\nagency. Mrs. Guerra, employed by\nthe company since 1952, is media\ndirector.\nThe new officers were elected\nat a board of directors meeting\nmarking the beginning of the 12th\nyear for the agency which now\nhas an annual gross billing of two\nKEEP YOUR CAR ON THE GO\nHave It Serviced At\nRAY\u2019S AMOCO\n29901 Federal Hwy., Homestead Phone CI 7-9969\nOverseas Bait Tackle Shop, Inc.\nBAIT TACKLE TACKLE REPAIRS\nINFORMATION\nJohnson Motor Sales and Service\nP. O. BOX 1386, HOMESTEAD, FLA.\nPhone CI 7-1449\nSweetest Running Johnsons Ever\nAd Agency\nmillion dollars. It ranks as Flori\nda\u2019s largest advertising agency.\n\u201cOur volume of business in 1957\nwas the heaviest in the company\u2019s\nhistory, and our billing in January\nand February of this year were\nhigher than for the corresponding\nperiod of last year,\u201d Bishopric\nsaid.\nBenjamin C. Green, director of\nresearch, was added to the board\nof directors at the meeting.\nReelected officers and board\nmembers were President Bishop\nric, executive vice president Jack\nI. Green and vice presidents W.\nArthur Fielden and Charles H.\nWhitebrook.","height":"28010","width":"18875"}}
